Distractor patterns to recognize.

A few recurring traps show up across the question pool, and knowing them saves time. When a customer wants minimum operational overhead, pick the managed service, a function over an instance, serverless containers over self-managed ones. When the question says encrypt at rest with a customer-managed key, that's a customer key, not the default. For most cost-effective plus infrequent access, it's usually an infrequent-access storage class or an archive tier, and you check the latency tolerance to pick which. Classic-era options, the old load balancer or a self-managed network-address-translation instance, are usually wrong in modern questions.

Multi-zone is for failover, not read scaling, while read replicas are for read scaling, not automatic failover, so a question about increasing read throughput wants read replicas. For the messaging triplet, a work queue means the queue service, push fan-out means the notification service, and an event bus with routing rules means the event bridge. A security group is stateful and per-instance, while an access control list is stateless and per-subnet, so blocking one address at the subnet level means the access control list. Object storage and the key-value store get free gateway endpoints, while everything else uses paid interface endpoints. Web caching at the edge means the content network, while non-web global routing means the global accelerator. And cross-account, federated, or temporary access means assuming a role; long-lived keys are almost always the wrong answer.

The meta-rule: when a question offers a tempting old-school answer alongside a newer managed primitive, the newer one is almost always correct.
